networkBlogs.title: Australia
networkBlogs.short_description:
Research to Research to practice events connect practitioners with researchers, policy makers and practice experts within Australia and from around the world via seminars and webinars. These seminars provide opportunities for practitioners to become familiar with, inspired and challenged by new evidence, ideas and practice methods and provides an opportunity to network with peers . All research to practice events are live streamed and supported by a range of practice notes and learning resources to help practitioners apply this knowledge to their everyday practice.

Videos and practice notes from the November seminar See, Understand and Respond to Child Sexual Abuse will be published shortly. See the Child Sexual Abuse practice kit for more information.

networkBlogs.title: New Zealand
networkBlogs.short_description:
Each year, the Office of the Senior Practitioner hosts the FACS Practice Conference, which brings together over 500 FACS practitioners, plus more live streamers, to reflect, learn and share knowledge and skills about practice with children and families.

Practitioners are able to hear local and international speakers, take part in workshops and master classes and network with fellow colleagues, speakers and presenters.

While each conference focuses on a particular theme, practice always remains at the heart of learning and new knowledge. Practitioners who attend the conference always talk about how the learning from the conference inspires and excites them to try new and different things in their work.

Videos of each of the keynote speakers at the last three conferences are available to view on these pages.

Watch this space for information about the next Practice Conference in 2017.

articleDetails.content:
A Labor government would triple the cost of temporary foreign worker visas to encourage bosses to look locally.

Opposition Leader Bill Shorten will make the announcement during a pre - budget speech to the McKell Institute in Sydney on Wednesday.

A four - year visa would cost about $1600 a year,up from the $575 a yearfor two years under the Turnbull government & #39;s new scheme.

The extra revenue from the visa fees would be used to establish a new skills training fund, Mr Shorten will say.

Labor would also create a new visa to attract the best and brightest to Australia in the areas of science, medicine, academia, research and technology and a new independent, labour market testing body would determine what skills are needed.

The new authority would create a single Skills Shortage Occupations List and advise government on skills shortages and future skills needs.

heading 1

heading 2

heading 3

Mr Shorten new policy comes in response to the government& decision last month to abolish the 457 visa program and replace it with two new temporary skills shortage visas, alongside tougher English testing.
